e]][[#New cities|*]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Weifang]][[#New cities|*]]\n* {{flagicon|NAM}} [[Windhoek]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Winnipeg]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Wuxi]][[#New cities|*]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Xining]][[#New cities|*]]\n* {{flagicon|ARM}} [[Yerevan]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Zhuhai]][[#New cities|*]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== No longer classified ==\nThe following cities were included in the 2016 edition, but not in the 2018 edition.\n\n{{div col|colwidth=10em}}\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Aligarh]]\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Allahabad]]\n* {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Bern]]\n* {{flagicon|KGZ}} [[Bishkek]]\n* {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Chihuahua City|Chihuahua]]\n* {{flagicon|ISR}} [[Haifa]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Honolulu]]\n* {{flagicon|TGO}} [[Lom\u00e9]]\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Mannheim]]\n* {{flagicon|IRQ}} [[Mosul]]\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Nagpur]]\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Nashik]]\n* {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Natal, Rio Grande do Norte|Natal]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Omaha, Nebraska|Omaha]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]\n* {{flagicon|BRA}} [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]]\n* {{flagicon|LBY}} [[Tripoli]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Global city]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lboro.ac.uk/gawc/ Globalization and World Cities Research Network official website]\n\n{{Loughborough University}}\n\n[[Category:Research institutes in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Social science institutes]]\n[[Category:Think tanks established in 1998]]\n[[Category:1998 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Loughborough University]]\n[[Category:Global studies research]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Globalization and World Cities Research Network''', commonly abbreviated to '''GaWC''', is a [[think tank]] that studies the relationships between [[global city|world cities]] in the context of [[globalization]]. It is based in the [[geography]] department of [[Loughborough University]] in [[Leicestershire]], [[United Kingdom]]. GaWC was founded by [[Peter J. Taylor]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite book|last=Taylor|first=Peter J.|title=World city network: a global urban analysis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RKpvD7nvBKUC&pg=PR9|accessdate=2010-10-10|year=2004|publisher=Routledge|isbn=0-415-30249-8|page=ix}}</ref>  Together with Jon Beaverstock and [[Richard G. Smith (geographer)|Richard G. Smith]], they create the GaWC's bi-annual categorization of world cities into \"Alpha\", \"Beta\", and \"Gamma\" tiers, based upon their international connectedness.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Donald|first1=Stephanie|last2=Gammack|first2=John G.|title=Tourism and the branded city|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gcAx3bjuC98C&pg=PA23|accessdate=2010-10-10|year=2007 |publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing]] |location=London|isbn=0-7546-4829-X|page=23 }}</ref>\n\n== GaWC city classification ==\nThe GaWC examines cities worldwide to narrow them down to a roster of world cities, then ranks these based on their connectivity through four \"advanced producer services\": accountancy, advertising, banking/finance, and law.<ref name = \"intro\">{{cite web |url= https://www.lboro.ac.uk/gawc/world2018link.html |title=GaWC City Link Classification 2018|publisher=Lboro.ac.uk |date= 13 November 2018|accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> The GaWC inventory ranks city [[economics]] more heavily than political or cultural factors. Beyond the categories of \"Alpha\" world cities (with four sub-categories), \"Beta\" world cities (three sub-categories), and \"Gamma\" world cities (three sub-categories), the GaWC cities include additional cities at \"High sufficiency\" and \"Sufficiency\" level.\n\nThe 2004 rankings added several new indicators while continuing to rank city economics more heavily than political or cultural factors. The 2008 roster, similar to the 1998 version, is sorted into categories of Alpha world cities (with four sub-categories), Beta world cities (three sub-categories), Gamma world cities (three sub-categories), and additional cities with High sufficiency or Sufficiency presence.\n\n== 2018 city classification ==\nThe cities in the 2018 classification are as follows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lboro.ac.uk/gawc/world2018t.html|title=The World According to GaWC 2018|date=14 November 2018|publisher=Globalization and World Cities Research Network|accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|New cities}}\nCities which did not appear in the 2016 edition of the classification are marked with *. \n\n=== Alpha ===\nAlpha level cities are linked to major economic states and regions into the world economy, and are classified into four sections, Alpha ++, Alpha +, Alpha, and Alpha \u2212 cities.\n\n==== Alpha ++ ====\nAlpha ++ cities are cities most integrated with the global economy: \n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* {{flagicon|GBR}} [[London]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[New York City]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Alpha + ====\nAlpha + cities are highly integrated cities, filling advanced service needs:\n{{div col|colwidth=10em}}\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Beijing]]\n* {{flagicon|ARE}} [[Dubai]]\n* {{flagicon|HKG}} [[Hong Kong]]\n* {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Paris]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Shanghai]]\n* {{flagicon|SIN}} [[Singapore]]\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Sydney]]\n* {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Tokyo]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Alpha ====\n{{div col|colwidth=10em}}\n* {{flagicon|THA}} [[Bangkok]]\n* {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Brussels]]\n* {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Buenos Aires]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Chicago]]\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Frankfurt]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Guangzhou]]\n* {{flagicon|TUR}} [[Istanbul]]\n* {{flagicon|IDN}} [[Jakarta]]\n* {{flagicon|MAS}} [[Kuala Lumpur]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Los Angeles]]\n* {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Madrid]]\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Melbourne]]\n* {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Mexico City]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Miami]]\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Milan]]\n* {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Moscow]]\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Mumbai]]\n* {{flagicon|BRA}} [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n* {{flagicon|KOR}} [[Seoul]]\n* {{flagicon|TAI}} [[Taipei]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Toronto]]\n* {{flagicon|POL}} [[Warsaw]]\n* {{flagicon|SUI}} [[Z\u00fcrich]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Alpha \u2212 ====\n\n{{div col|colwidth=10em}}\n* {{flagicon|NLD}} [[Amsterdam]]\n* {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Barcelona]]\n* {{flagicon|COL}} [[Bogot\u00e1]]\n* {{flagicon|HUN}} [[Budapest]]\n* {{flagicon|IRL}} [[Dublin]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Houston]]\n* {{flagicon|RSA}} [[Johannesburg]]\n* {{flagicon|POR}} [[Lisbon]]\n* {{flagicon|LUX}} [[Luxembourg City]]\n* {{flagicon|PHL}} [[Manila]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Montreal]]\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Munich]]\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[New Delhi]]\n* {{flagicon|CZE}} [[Prague]]\n* {{flagicon|SAU}} [[Riyadh]]\n* {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Rome]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[San Francisco]]\n* {{flagicon|CHL}} [[Santiago]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Shenzhen]]\n* {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Stockholm]]\n* {{flagicon|AUT}} [[Vienna]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Washington, D.C.]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n=== Beta ===\nBeta level cities are cities that link moderate economic regions to the world economy and are classified in three sections, Beta +, Beta, and Beta &minus; cities.\n\n==== Beta + ====\n{{div col|colwidth=10em}}\n* {{flagicon|GRE}} [[Athens]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Atlanta]]\n* {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Auckland]]\n* {{flagicon|IND}} [[Bangalore]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Boston]]\n* {{flagicon|ROM}} [[Bucharest]]\n* {{flagicon|EGY}} [[Cairo]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Chengdu]]\n* {{flagicon|DNK}} [[Copenhagen]]\n* {{flagicon|USA}} [[Dallas]]\n* {{flagicon|QAT}} [[Doha]]\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} [[D\u00fcsseldorf]]\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Hamburg]]\n* {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Hangzhou]]\n* {{flagicon|VIE}} [[Hanoi]]\n* {{flagicon|VIE}} [[Ho Chi Minh City]]\n* {{flagicon|PER}} [[Lima]]\n* {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Perth]]\n* {{flagicon|ISR}} [[Tel Aviv]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Vancouver]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==== Beta ====\n{{div col|colwidth=10em}}\n* {{flagicon|UAE}} [[Abu Dhabi]]\n* {{flagicon|LBN}} [[Beirut]]\n* {{flagicon|DEU}} [[Berlin]]\n* {{flagic